Ukraine on the Way to Europe
"East is East and West is West, and never the twain shall meet," said Rudyard Kipling once.
Undoubtedly, Ukraine is located in the east, but in Eastern Europe.
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became the predominant goal for many of us.
The way there was, however, not always paved with success, if it was paved at all.
But the result of the parliamentary elections on March 31 has shown that the Ukrainians are still determined to go this way.
I am a social democrat and was never a member of the communist party, although I was quite successful as a lawyer during the time of the Soviet Union.
There is no doubt in my mind that our "Soviet" heritage is largely responsible for the difficulties Ukraine faces in finding its way toward Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country had an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The vast agricultural areas were practically paralyzed by outdated machinery and the inertia of state-run agriculture modeled after the Soviet system.
The rural population sank deep into filth and poverty.
Low wages make life here very difficult, pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is huge.
But our Soviet heritage does not justify everything.
We messed up the reform all by ourselves.
For often we wanted to import proven concepts from the West—in private property, a free market economy, strict observance of human rights, the creation of a civil society, representative democracy—in a weakened form, and believed that this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic tendencies in politics, the Supreme Council (the parliament of Ukraine) has, over the years, adopted civil rights and criminal law, land, family, and economic rights, which is somewhat akin to a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that had been cut off from European history for centuries was often painful, but it has gained momentum, even though we do not necessarily see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as open, sentimental, friendly, and family-oriented, but also chaotic and indifferent, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
Nevertheless, we are Europeans.
You can see that on the streets and squares of Kyiv.
Today, drivers let pedestrians cross the street, as in Geneva or Munich (while pedestrians in Moscow still have to get out of the way of inconsiderate drivers).
In Kyiv, there is now a lively café scene and friendly public squares where people can pause and enjoy life.
The young people learn English, German, and French, they can handle computers and surf the internet in internet cafes.
But these are just the sentimental digressions of someone who loves Kyiv very much.
The sober gaze of the professional politician that I am sees deeper changes.
Over the last ten years, there has been a development from total rejection of reforms, through a policy of half-hearted reforms driven by corrupt motives, to a gradual introduction of Western practices.
The administrative reform clearly illustrates this.
First, the reform of the state provoked a hostile attitude both among bureaucrats and ordinary citizens.
A drastic and thoughtless reduction of civil servants in the public service began.
It was a "formula F" reform: the state had to shrink, people assumed, and then the government would already run smoothly.
No one thought about how countries like France or Switzerland somehow manage to thrive with large state apparatuses.
Because the problem is not only a problem of size, but also of organization and efficiency.
The realization that the government does not necessarily become better simply by wielding the red pen led us to the second stage in our reform process.
Slowly, the state was reformed in a more thoughtful way.
New departments and positions for state secretaries with clearly defined areas of responsibility were established.
This stabilized the work of the government ministries.
At the beginning, the authority delegated to these new areas was somewhat too broad to enable them to carry out their work more effectively.
Now they more or less function normally.
Ukrainians may sometimes be annoyed by these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they are increasingly accepting them as necessary (albeit reluctantly).
Reasonable politicians accept them as well.
Only radicals and populists — of which there are still far too many among us — can afford to take an indifferent stance toward a more efficient state.
Taming our radicals and the radical impulse was not easy.
Why?
Ukraine had been too long a province of the USSR and the Tsarist Empire, the most important one, but still a province.
That has shaped our mentality. For radicalism is a byproduct of provincial inferiority complexes.
An overwhelming feeling of inferiority and our efforts to deny it have led to the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincial man can by no means admit his own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
To the extent that we shed our provincial impulse to feel the need to defend ourselves, we open ourselves up to the best that others can offer us.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire was mocked as "the sick man of Europe."
Since 1991, the Ukrainians have had to realize that their country had inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
Over the course of a decade, we may have even contributed to becoming even more ill, but the recently held elections, which have stripped the Communists of their dominant position in the Supreme Council and significantly curtailed the power of the "powerful parties" around President Kuchma, have pushed our provincial radicals to the margins of politics.
The reform parties and the European parties have won.
As Europeans on the periphery or at least as a people on the edge of Europe, we want to establish a society in which there are no outsiders or marginalized individuals.
As the great and at that time already American writer Vladimir Nabokov said in the 1970s: "Of all nature's achievements, the most astonishing is probably the survival of the weakest."
The long, hardship-filled journey to Europe has helped a weak new nation become strong and survive.
